Use a sharp kitchen knife to cut the avocado from top to bottom. Note that with the avocado on its side, you will be making a horizontal cut through the long side of the fruit rather than the short width side. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Securely grip the avocado in your non-dominant hand. If necessary, hold the fruit with a towel to give yourself more traction and a firmer grip. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d2/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d2/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Start from the narrower end, or the "top," and across to the wider end, or the "bottom. "{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You will need to cut around the pit at the center of the fruit. You will not be able to cut through it. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/60/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/60/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

This is the safest technique you can use to remove the pit of the avocado. Slide the tip of the spoon in between the pit and the surrounding flesh. Gently push the spoon underneath the pit, following the side of the pit as closely as possible. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/48/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/48/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Circle the spoon around the pit to loosen it from the surrounding flesh on all sides. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Glide the spoon back under the pit of the avocado and lift it straight up and out. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/de/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/de/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slip the tip of a large metal serving spoon into the flesh of the avocado as close the the skin as possible. Try to insert the spoon into the flesh before the dark green portion of the flesh to preserve as much of the flesh as possible. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e0/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e0/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Gently push the spoon underneath the flesh, following the curve of the skin as closely as possible. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/15/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/15/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slowly glide the spoon around the perimeter of the fruit to completely sever the flesh from the skin. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Peel-an-Avocado-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
